            <h2>Cat Care</h2>
            <ol>
                <li><strong>Provide Proper Nutrition</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Feed your cat high-quality commercial cat food or a balanced homemade diet as recommended by your veterinarian.</li>
                        <li>Follow feeding guidelines based on your cat’s age, size, and activity level.</li>
                        <li>Ensure your cat has access to fresh, clean water at all times.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Regular Exercise</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Encourage play with toys that simulate hunting behavior, such as wand toys and laser pointers.</li>
                        <li>Provide climbing structures like cat trees or shelves to allow your cat to climb and explore.</li>
                        <li>Rotate toys regularly to keep your cat engaged and active.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Veterinary Care</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Schedule regular vet visits for health checkups and vaccinations.</li>
                        <li>Administer flea, tick, and worm preventives as recommended by your vet.</li>
                        <li>Consider spaying or neutering your cat to prevent unwanted litters and reduce certain health risks.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Grooming</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Brush your cat’s coat regularly to prevent matting and reduce shedding.</li>
                        <li>Bathe your cat as needed using a cat-specific shampoo.</li>
                        <li>Trim your cat’s nails regularly to prevent overgrowth and discomfort.</li>
                        <li>Check and clean your cat’s ears regularly to prevent infections.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Litter Box Care</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Provide a clean litter box and scoop it daily.</li>
                        <li>Change the litter regularly and wash the litter box with soap and water.</li>
                        <li>Place the litter box in a quiet, accessible location.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Training and Enrichment</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Teach your cat to use a scratching post to prevent furniture damage.</li>
                        <li>Provide interactive toys and puzzle feeders to keep your cat mentally stimulated.</li>
                        <li>Use positive reinforcement techniques like treats and praise to encourage good behavior.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Safe Environment</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ensure your home is safe by removing hazards like toxic plants and small objects that could be swallowed.</li>
                        <li>Provide a comfortable and secure space for your cat to rest and feel safe.</li>
                        <li>Keep windows and balconies secure to prevent accidental falls.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>Love and Attention</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Spend quality time with your cat, showing them affection and playtime.</li>
                        <li>Pay attention to changes in your cat’s behavior or health and seek veterinary care if needed.</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
            </ol>
